Introduction

Investigation on the nature of organotin derivatives remains a central focus of fundamental research, owing to the enormous variety of intriguing structural topologies and their unexpected properties for potential practical applications . It is well known that the organotin carboxylates have versatile molecular structures both in solid and solution, such as monomers, dimers, tetramers, oligomeric ladders, hexameric drums, etc. . It has also been demonstrated that other structural types are formed due to the presence of additional heteroatom sites (S, N, O, etc.) along with a carboxylate moiety . In our previous work, we have reported several interesting organotin structures derived from mercapto-carboxylate ligands through self-assembly, such as six-tin-nuclear 32-membered macrocyclic complexes, eight-tin-nuclear macrocyclic complex with 2-mercapto-4-methyl-5-thiazoleacetic acid and a 3D framework with meso-2,3-dimercaptosuccinic acid . To continue the work in this field, we selected another carboxylic acid tetrahydro-2-fural acid containing additional oxygen heteroatom as bridging ligand and obtained two different structures in different condition. In this paper we reported the synthesis and characterization of the two interesting structures.

Results and discussion

Synthesis and spectra

The synthesis procedures are shown in  .

Complexes 1 and 2 are synthesized by different methods, complex 1 is obtained under conventional method and complex 2 is synthesized under solvothermal condition. The infrared data of organotin carboxylates are usually used to predict their solid-state structures. The bridging carboxylates of organotin compounds are simply characterized by infrared spectroscopy by the shift of ν(CO2) bands, as compared with the parent carboxylic acid. In the IR spectra of the two complexes C16H32O6Sn2 (1), C36H60Na2O18Sn2 (2), the ν as(CO2) and the ν s(CO2) stretchings appear at 1591, 1590, 1568, 1395, 1382 and 1322cm-1, respectively. According to the literature, the magnitude of Δν (ν as - ν s) can indicate the coordination modes of carboxylate groups . For complex 2, these Δν values (208 and 246) indicate that both bridging bi- and monodentate coordination modes of the carboxylate groups are present, while for complex 1 (Δν =196cm-1) only bidentate coordination mode is detected. Furthermore, the presences of Sn-O vibrations for both complexes also confirm the coordination of carboxylate groups to tin. The aforementioned conclusions are confirmed by the X-ray crystallography spectroscopy.

This conclusion accords well with the IR data. In the <ce:sup loc="post">13</ce:sup>C NMR spectra, the position of the carboxylate carbon moved to the lower field, as compared with the free ligands, indicating participation of the carboxylic group in coordination to tin . These results are consistent with the X-ray crystallography spectroscopy.</ce:para>
